Peel and finely dice the @garlic clove{1} and the @shallot{1}. Pre-heat the #oven{} to 200 degrees.

Once the oven is hot put the @pine nuts{1.5%tbsp} on a #baking tray{}. Put the baking tray in the oven for ~{2%mins} to brown them off.

> Keep an eye on your nuts as they can burn very easily.

Heat @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #nonstick pan{} on medium heat. Once hot add in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Mix in the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can}, the @dried Italian herbs{2%tsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a few grinds of @black pepper{a few grinds}. Add @sugar{1/4%tsp}(if you have some) and cook on low heat until the sauce thickens.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} on medium-high heat in the largest #pan{} you have. Once hot, tip in the @baby spinach{1} and put a #lid{} on for ~{1%minute}. Take off the lid and give the spinach a good stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Transfer the spinach to a #colander{} and leave on the side.

In a #bowl{} mix the @ricotta cheese{1} with @shallot{1}(very finely diced) and @salt{1/4%tsp}. Once the spinach is cool, squeeze every last drop of water out with your hands.

> Or you can squeeze it dry in a kitchen towel. Chop the spinach very finely and then mix it thoroughly into the ricotta mixture.

Lightly coat the bottom of an #ovenproof dish{} with some @olive oil{} and put a layer of @lasagne sheets{1/2} on the bottom. Spread 1/4 of your ricotta and spinach mixture onto the pasta and sprinkle over 1/4 of the pine nuts. Spread 1/3 of your tomato sauce across the ricotta. Put a layer of pasta on the top to cover everything.

Repeat the process until you have used all of the ingredients.

> You want to end by spreading 1/4 of the ricotta mixture and the pine nuts on the very top. Sprinkle over some @grated hard Italian style cheese{2%tbsp} and put in the oven for ~{30%mins}.